Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Cut the @aubergine{1} in half lengthways and then
chop into 2cm cubes. Chop the @celery stick{1} into ½cm chunks. Peel and grate
half the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, then remove the
cores from the @red pepper{1} and @green pepper{1/2} and chop into 2cm chunks.
We like our @olives{15} whole, but chop them if you prefer!

Spread the aubergine and peppers evenly on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with
@olive oil{1} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Roast on the top
shelf of your oven until soft and a little crispy around the edges,
~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot,
add the celery with a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{}. Meanwhile,
slice open the @Tuscan pork sausage{250%g}, remove the meat and discard the skin.

When the celery is soft, after about ~{5%minutes}, add the grated garlic. Cook
for ~{1%minute} more. Add the sausage meat and use a #wooden spoon{} to break
it up. Cook for ~{5%minutes}. Pour in the @chopped tomatoes{1}, then fill the
tin(s) a quarter with water and add to the pan for the caponata. If you are
cooking for three people, add the @tomato puree{1}. Add the olives,
@white wine vinegar{1} and another pinch of @salt{}. Stir, then simmer
for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Once the veggies have roasted, add them to the caponata. Turn your #grill{} to
high. Cut the @ciabatta{1} in half (as if you were making a sandwich), place on
another baking tray and toast on each side until golden brown. Once toasted,
cut the remaining garlic clove in half and rub it across the cut side of each
ciabatta. Drizzle over the @olive oil{1} (amount specified in ingredient list)
and season with a pinch of @salt{}.

When your caponata has thickened, serve it in #bowls{}. It can be eaten with
cutlery or by using the ciabatta as a small edible shovel!

> Patrick learned how to make this dish whilst filming in the beautiful coastal
> town of Catania and (in a fairly risky move), he has decided to recreate it
> with a few of his own flavours. Italians are fiercely protective of their
> recipes so, for his sake, let's keep this one under our hats!